{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477092"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:56:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:56:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14176"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14176"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.19,0.11,0.49,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6859"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100858"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6859"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14176"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83280"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1519"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3516"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15629"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44199"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100858"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-day-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parents with a two-day history of poor feeding and lethargy. He was born at term with no complications and was discharged home on day two. He is exclusively breastfed. He has had fewer wet nappies in the last 24 hours. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 170/min, blood pressure 70/40 mmHg, respiratory rate 60/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His fontanelle is sunken, and his skin has a doughy feel. His mucous membranes are dry. He weighs 2.8 kg, down from his birth weight of 3.2 kg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum sodium: 158 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum potassium: 3.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum urea: 15 mmol/L (2.5-6.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 120 \u00b5mol/L (20-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate fluid management strategy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rapid correction with 0.45% sodium chloride over four hours","Rapid correction with 0.9% sodium chloride over four hours","Gradual correction with 5% dextrose over 48 hours","Gradual correction with 0.9% sodium chloride + 5% dextrose over 48 hours","Rapid correction with 5% dextrose over four hours"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a neonate with hypernatraemic dehydration, likely due to inadequate fluid intake in the setting of establishing breastfeeding. The clinical features include weight loss (\u0026gt;10%), poor feeding, lethargy, tachycardia, and the characteristic doughy feel of the skin. The investigations confirm hypernatraemia (sodium 158 mmol/L) with associated acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe hypernatraemia in this neonate is due to concentrational hypernatraemia, secondary to water loss exceeding sodium loss. Inadequate fluid intake from poor breastfeeding has led to significant dehydration, causing a reduction in total body water while total body sodium remains relatively preserved. As a result, the serum sodium concentration rises. This is the most common mechanism of hypernatraemia in neonates with feeding difficulties. It differs from hypernatraemia caused by sodium overload (such as improper formula preparation or salt poisoning) or sodium retention (as seen in certain renal or endocrine disorders), where there is an actual increase in total body sodium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGradual correction with 0.9% sodium chloride + 5% dextrose over 48 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management strategy. In hypernatraemic dehydration, it\u0027s crucial to correct the sodium slowly to prevent rapid shifts in osmolality, which can lead to cerebral oedema and seizures. The general rule is to reduce serum sodium by no more than 0.5 mmol/L per hour or 10-12 mmol/L in 24 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid correction with 0.9% sodium chloride over four hours\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as it risks causing cerebral oedema due to the rapid shift in osmolality. This approach could lead to serious neurological complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid correction with 0.45% sodium chloride over four hours\u003C/strong\u003E is also unsuitable. Not only is the correction too rapid, but hypotonic fluids can cause a dangerously quick drop in serum sodium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGradual correction with 5% dextrose over 48 hours\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it doesn\u0027t address the sodium imbalance. While the gradual approach is correct, using only dextrose would further lower the serum sodium concentration too quickly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid correction with 5% dextrose over four hours\u003C/strong\u003E combines two inappropriate approaches: rapid correction and the use of hypotonic fluids. This could lead to a dangerous drop in serum sodium and potential cerebral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing hypernatraemic dehydration in infants, it\u0027s important to remember that the condition often develops slowly over days, and therefore should be corrected slowly. The underlying cause (in this case, likely inadequate breastfeeding) should also be addressed. Close monitoring of serum electrolytes, urine output, and neurological status is essential during rehydration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypernatraemic dehydration in infants is often caused by inadequate breastfeeding or improper formula preparation.","Clinical signs of hypernatraemic dehydration in infants may be subtle, with a doughy feel to the skin being characteristic.","Gradual correction of hypernatraemia is crucial to prevent cerebral oedema and seizures in infants presenting with hypernatraemic dehydration"],"references":["Arora I, Juneja H, Bhandekar H, Chandankhede M. Neonatal hypernatremic dehydration in breastfed neonates: a prospective study unmasking the influences of breastfeeding practices and early weight monitoring. J Matern Fetal Neonatal Med. 2024 Dec;37(1):2299568. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1080/14767058.2023.2299568","Durrani NUR, Imam AA, Soni N. Hypernatremia in Newborns: A Practical Approach to Management. Biomed Hub. 2022 May 19;7(2):55-69. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35950014/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83280"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14176"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83280"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-27T17:13:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-27T17:14:20+09:30"},"relati